<br/>


			<h3 id="Intro">Introduction</h3><b>Key Features</b><br />â¢	This is a leading-edge and growing subject area, currently undergoing a considerable amount of development on a world-wide scale.<br />â¢	Exciting job opportunities will be available to you on graduating in numerous industrial sectors.<br />â¢	You will be given the opportunity to develop your transferable skills such as team-working, problem-solving, time management and presentation skills, all of which will enhance your employability status on graduating.<br />â¢	The programme uses innovative teaching methods to provide an effective teaching and learning environment. <br /><br /><b>About this course</b><br />We are surrounded by âsmartâ gadgets and systems. Once the topic of science-fiction programmes, yesterdayâs seemingly impossible ideas have become part of our every day lives. A smart system is defined as one that automatically adjusts or adapts its behaviour in response to external stimuli. Existing applications of smart technologies include: smart homes where energy levels can be monitored and adapted to external conditions (controlling heating and lighting remotely from your mobile phone); supermarket loyalty cards where personal shopping trends dictate which money-off coupons will be sent; smart cards that let you access products and services within a defined area. <br /><br />The question is what will be the smart systems of tomorrow? Our clothing might have smart labelling to allow washing machines to pick the best wash cycle. Our fridges might order shopping for us automatically over the Internet. Our cars might be equipped with specialized sensors and wireless communication systems to allow us to travel on automated highways, enabling high-speed travel in closely spaced convoys. The health of the elderly and disabled might be monitored in their own houses, reducing the need for them to move into care homes. Increasingly, companies in various sectors of industry are looking for talented graduates to help develop products and systems using the most up-to-date thinking in order to give them a competitive edge. This programme has been developed to satisfy this demand. It is academically challenging and will develop your skills in programming, system planning and design and computer interfacing. In addition, you will be introduced to a wide range of smart systems technologies.<br/><br/>	
		
		

			<h3 id="Themes">Core Themes</h3><b>What you study<br />Stage 1 </b><br />Computer hardware; programming; web authoring; introduction to smart systems; team-based project.<br /><br /><b>Stage 2 </b><br />Systems planning & design; smart systems development; networking; databases; controlling devices; web development.<br /><br /><b>Stage 3 </b><br />Business skills; smart systems application; mobile computing; databases; networking; controlling devices; group project.<br /><br /><b>Stage 4</b><br />Honours project; XML technologies; intelligent systems; mobile phone technology; controlling devices.<br /><br /><b>How you learn</b><br />This programme uses a studio-based approach to teaching and learning. Lectures, tutorials, and laboratory-based activities all take part in a dedicated flexible learning space. You will spend around 15 hours per week in a supervised study environment. Lectures are used to present the key concepts, theories and techniques throughout the programme. Tutorials and lab-based activities allow you to explore these concepts in more detail and increase your understanding of the subject, while allowing you to develop your competence in technological and theoretical work.<br /><br />During the programme you will also be expected to actively participate in discussion groups, design reviews, lectures, practical tutorials and private study.<br /><br /><b>How you are assessed</b><br />In stages 1 and 2, the emphasis is on building up a portfolio based on the topics being studied. Formative assessment in the form of informal presentations, practical demonstrations and group discussions takes place throughout term 1. This provides guidance on portfolio development ready for formal assessment in term 2.<br /><br />At stage 3, a large group project is again assessed via portfolio. Other topics are assessed with a mix of coursework and written examinations. <br /><br />The honours project makes up a significant part of stage 4. This includes a dissertation, practical development work and oral presentation. The specialist modules, which run in parallel, are assessed via a mix of coursework and written examinations.<br /><br /><br />	
		
		
		

			<h3 id="Career">Career Opportunities:</h3>Developments in industrial, political and social issues has resulted in an increasing interest in concepts such as eCities, eHealth, eGovernance, eLearning, development of smart devices and smart buildings. As a result of this, there is a demand for high calibre graduates with knowledge of advanced or âsmartâ systems and products. Smart technologies themselves are in the spotlight, in particular, the application of these technologies in areas such as security and identity management. Organisations all over the world have recognised the potential of smart applications and are looking for talented graduates to help them with implementation. In the Dundee area alone, companies such as NCR, NHS Tayside and Dundee City Council are all involved in the application of smart systems. Further afield, large organisations producing white-goods, electrical products and car manufacturers are increasingly embracing smart technologies to enhance their product range. The leading-edge nature of this programme means that you will be exposed to the most recent developments in the field, therefore opening the door to an exciting career anywhere in the world. Through the Universityâs own enterprise initiatives, there is also the opportunity for students to set up their own companies.<br /><br />	

		
